    "source": "dokumen.pub_daring-pairings-a-master-sommelier-matches-distinctive-wines-with-recipes-from-his-favorite-chefs-9780520945562.pdf_page_111",
    "contenu": "The document discusses the various aspects of Grüner Veltliner, a type of white wine, highlighting its regional growth, flavor complexity, and its classifications under different quality metrics. It also compares Grüner Veltliner to other wines, discusses serving suggestions and aging preferences.\n\nHere’s the structured content from the text:\n\n### Overview\n- **Popularity and Regions**: Grüner Veltliner is gaining popularity outside Austria and is planted in regions including the Czech Republic, Hungary, New Zealand, and California's Napa Valley.\n- **Flavor Profile**: The wine can be from lemon cucumber to green bean, and generally combines pepper with a lemony and balanced alcohol content.\n- **Importance of Vineyard and Region:** The region and vineyard contribute significantly to the complexity and ripeness of the fruit in the wines.\n\n### Classification of Grüner Veltliner\n- **General Classification**\n  - **Vintner’s Choices**: Variations based on age, type of growth season, ripeness of grapes at harvest, use of oak.\n  - **Wine Range Style**: From lean and mean to full and fat, including unfermented and fermented styles.\n  \n- **Specific Categories**:\n  - **Tafelwein** (Table wine): Simple, everyday consumption quality.\n  - **Qualitätswein** (Quality wine): Higher standard of quality.\n  - **Prädikatswein** (Certified wine): Determined by the higher sugar content of grape must.\n  \n- **Sub-Classifications in Sweeter Styles**:\n  - **Kabinett**: Generally sweeter.\n  - **Spätlese**: Overripe bunch-harvested grapes, resulting in a sweet taste.\n  - **Auslese** and **Trockenbeerenauslese**: Even riper and sweeter, with Auslese having less alcoholic strength, and Trockenbeerenauslese being very rare and sweet.\n\n### Regions with Specific Terms (for Wachau Region, Austria)\n- **Steinfeder**: Lightest variety of Grüner Veltliner.\n- **Federspiel**: Well-developed and elegant.\n- **Smaragd**: Most expressive and has more viscosity.\n\n### Aging and Pairing\n- **Aging**: While commonly consumed young and vibrant, the wine benefits from aging, which can enhance its complexity and mineral character.\n- **Pairing**: Special attention is required for pairing Grüner Veltliner with food due to its complexity and aroma profile.\n- **Barrique aging**: Small oak barrels are used to add texture and flavor, where the term \"barrique\" is a keyword for this process.\n\nThe document concludes by expressing a preference for tasting Grüner Veltliner both young and aged, emphasizing its unique flavor profile and aging potential."
  },
