    "contenu": "The document outlines a recipe for \"Braised Shank of Beef\" by Fergus Henderson at St. John, London, United Kingdom. Here is the structured content broken down into sections:\n\n### Title\n**Malbec Braised Shank of Beef**\n\n### Author and Location\n**Fergus Henderson, St. John, London, United Kingdom**\n\n### Servings\n**Makes 4 to 6 main-course servings**\n\n### Ingredients\n- 2 tablespoons rendered duck fat or unsalted butter\n- 1 (6- to 7-pound) whole beef shank\n- Salt and freshly ground black pepper\n- 12 shallots, peeled but left whole\n- 12 cloves garlic, peeled but left whole\n- 8 carrots, peeled and cut into ½-inch-thick slices\n- 1½ cups dry white wine\n- Bouquet garni of 6 fresh thyme sprigs, 3 fresh rosemary sprigs, ½ bunch fresh flat-leaf parsley, and 2 bay leaves, tied in a cheesecloth bundle\n- About 2 quarts chicken stock\n\n### Cooking Instructions\n1. **Preparation:**\n   - Preheat the oven to 275°F.\n   - In a large skillet, heat the duck fat over medium heat until hot.\n   - Season the whole shank with salt and pepper and add to the skillet.\n   - Brown the shank, turning as needed until well browned on all sides (about 10 minutes). Remove from the heat.\n\n2. **Assembling the Dish:**\n   - Select a baking dish or Dutch oven deep enough to accommodate all the ingredients.\n   - Assemble the ingredients in the dish in the following order: shallots, garlic, shank, carrots, wine, and bouquet garni.\n   - Pour enough stock to reach iceberg level—more covered than exposed—and cover tightly.\n\n3. **Cooking:**\n   - Place in the oven and cook for 6 hours.\n   - Check for doneness by stabbing the flesh with a knife tip; if it meets no resistance, it is ready.\n   - If not ready, return it to the oven for 15 to 30 minutes longer, and test again.\n\n4. **Finishing:**\n   - Remove from the oven, season with salt and pepper, and serve. The recipe advises not to worry about carving etiquette and to \"just attack!\"\n\n### Page Reference\n**Page 234, under title \"Malbec\"**"
  },
