    "contenu": "The document titled \"What a Wine Label Reads?\" describes the differences and features of wine labels from \"Old World\" and \"New World\" countries. Below is a structured summary of the content:\n\n1. **Pride and Sense of Place:**\n   - **Old World Wines:** Labels reflect a sense of place. These labels tend not to directly mention the grapes used, requiring consumer knowledge to deduce the type of wine.\n   - **New World Wines:** Labels make it easy to understand by directly mentioning the grapes used in fermentation.\n\n2. **Consumer Expectations and Changes:**\n   - **Old World Countries (e.g., France):** Expect wine users to be knowledgeable enough to understand details like the specific region and type of grapes. However, to compete globally, they are now shifting towards more reader-friendly labels.\n   - **Example Mentioned:**\n     - A typical label from the Old World like “Chateau Moulin de Grenet 2009 Lussac St. Emilion” indicates a transition towards clearer labels.\n\n3. **Detailed Labeling in Some Countries:**\n   - More detailed labels might include information about the Varietal Region, Producer, Vintage, Alcohol Percentage, Vineyard and Estate.\n\n4. **Simplified Example from New World:**\n    - A label from the New World like “Cakebread 2009 Merlot, Napa Valley” lists both grape variety and region clearly to aid consumer understanding.\n\nThis document emphasizes the evolving nature of wine labeling as producers from traditional wine-producing regions adapt to the global market's needs for clarity and ease of understanding."
