    "contenu": "This document provides insights into the Bordeaux wine region in France, emphasizing the famous red blend typically made from Merlot and Cabernet Sauvignon grapes. Here is a structured breakdown of the key information contained in the document:\n\n### Title: France: Bordeaux\n\n### Introduction: \n- **Primary Varietals**: Merlot and Cabernet Sauvignon.\n- **Blending**: These grapes are blended to create the Bordeaux Blend. \n\n### Classification and Wine Quality\n- Bordeaux wine production includes several classifications and terminologies:\n  - `CRU ARTISAN` and `CRU BOURGEOIS`\n  - `AOC` (Appellation d'Origine Contrôlée)\n  - `BORDEAUX SUPÉRIEUR`\n  - Generic wines labeled as `GENERIC BORDEAUX`\n\n### Vintages\n- **Notable years**: 2009, 2005, 2003, 1998.\n- Tip for collectors: Pay attention to the vintage year, especially for those labeled with their sub-appellation (such as the term \"Grand Vin de Bordeaux\") prominently.\n\n### Regions: Top Wines of Bordeaux Divided by Banks\n#### \"Left Bank\" Bordeaux\n- **Location**: West side of the Garonne River.\n- **Grape**: Predominantly Cabernet Sauvignon.\n- **Flavor Profile**: Wines from this area typically exhibit flavors of licorice, tobacco, cocoa, violet, and black current.\n\n#### \"Right Bank\" Bordeaux\n- **Location**: East side of the Garonne River.\n- **Grape**: Predominantly Merlot.\n- **Flavor Profile**: Wines often display notes of ripe strawberry, sweet red cherries, sumac, plum, and a refinement in texture.\n- **Area Feature**: Areas close to the river are known as “Côtes,” meaning slopes. These wines often have a Merlot blend that exhibits spicy red fruits, pepper, and herbs combined with suppleness and can age for 30 or more years old.\n\nThis document provides a comprehensive but succinct coverage of the main factors that define Bordeaux wine, focusing on varietals, classification, vintages, and regional characteristics of the wine produced on the banks of the Garonne River."
