    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_73",
    "contenu": "Sure, here is a structured representation of the content from the document titled \"CHEESE\".\n\n---\n\n### The Molds, Especially Penicillium Molds\n- **Oxygen Requirement:** Molds require oxygen to grow and are more tolerant to drier conditions than bacteria.\n- **Function:** Produce protein- and fat-digesting enzymes which enhance the texture and flavor of certain cheeses.\n- **Development:** Molds develop on the rind of almost any cheese that is not regularly wiped to prevent it. Ex. French St.-Nectaire develops a surface covered in lichen or bright yellow or orange spots.\n- **Varieties:** \n  - **Standard Garden Variety Molds:** Common in many cheeses, contribute to the large and various mold communities.\n  - **Penicillium:** Notable for also being the source of the antibiotic penicillin.\n\n### Blue Molds Penicillium Roqueforti\n- **Characteristics:** \n  - Colored blue, like in Roquefort cheese and provides veins of blue.\n  - *P. glaucum* colors the surface of Stilton and Gorgonzola and many aged cheeses.\n- **Growth Environment:** Thrives in low-oxygen conditions (5% compared to 21% in the air), often found in small fissures in cheeses.\n- **Function:** Breaks down fats, providing unique flavor and feel to cheeses like sheep’s milk and goat milk cheeses.\n- **Unique Products:** Metabolism produces methyl ketones and alcohols that result in the characteristic blue aroma.\n\n### White Molds\n- **Types:** Includes strains like Camembert and Brie; white molds on surface-ripened cow's milk cheeses.\n- **Effects:** Mainly break down protein contributing flavor notes of mushrooms, garlic, and ammonia.\n\n### Making Cheese\n- **Stages:**\n  1. **Initial:** Lactic acid bacteria convert milk sugar into lactic acid.\n  2. **Second Stage:** As cheese-making bacteria work, the cheesemaker adds rennet.\n  3. **Final Stage:** Involves more complex enzyme activity and draining of watery whey, ripening the curds.\n- **Elements:** \n  - Predominantly involves proteins and fat-digesting enzymes that contribute to flavor and texture.\n  - Described as a blend of knowledge and care by the cheesemaker, orchestrating many transformations.\n\n### Curdling\n- **Process:** Nearly all cheeses see the curdling of milk by acid and rennet.\n- **Acid and Rennet:** \n  - Acid creates a fine, fragile gel.\n  - Rennet contributes a robust, rubbery gel.\n- **Outcomes:** The relative contribution of acid and rennet affects how quickly the cheese deepens in taste and texture, determining the ultimate texture of the cheese.\n- **Key Factor:** In predominantly acid coagulation, curd forms over the course of hours."
  },
