    "contenu": "The document provided is titled \"Understanding Wines: Explaining Style and Quality\" and includes the section \"Introduction to Italy\" on page 120. This section discusses the diversity of grape varieties in Italy, their unique wine styles, and the wine laws that are applicable within Italian regions. Additionally, it includes a map highlighting the different wine regions of Italy.\n\n### Summary of Document Content:\n- **Title:** Understanding Wines: Explaining Style and Quality\n- **Page:** 120\n- **Section Title:** Introduction to Italy\n- **Key Points:**\n  - Italy has a large number of grape varieties, many of which are rarely seen outside of the country.\n  - The diversity of these varieties and their wine styles necessitates a brief introduction covering wine laws and their geographical relationship across Italy.\n\n### Details of Italian Wine Laws:\n- **Italian Wine Laws**:\n  - **General Information**: The following geographical indications are common across all Italian wine regions.\n  - **PDO Wines** (Protected Designation of Origin): Known as \"Denominazione di Origine Protetta\" (DOP) in Italy but may also be seen labeled using other traditional terms.\n  - **DOC Wines** (Controlled Designation of Origin): Known as \"Denominazione di Origine Controllata\" (DOC) referring to wines that must adhere to specific geographic boundaries and limitations on grape varieties and production methods.\n  - **DOCG Wines** (Controlled and Guaranteed Designation of Origin): Known as \"Denominazione di Origine Controllata e Garantita\" (DOCG), which must meet all DOC requirements plus additional production and quality standards set by the Ministry of Agriculture.\n  - **PGI Wines** (Protected Geographical Indication): Known as \"Indicazione Geografica Protetta\" (IGP), often labeled as \"Indicazione Geografica Tipica\" (IGT) in Italy.\n  - **Other Labeling Terms**:\n    - **Classico**: Used for wines from the original classified regions that have allowed expansion beyond their initial boundaries.\n    - **Riserva**: Indicates wines with higher alcohol levels and longer aging than the minimum required by appellation laws.\n\n### Map Overview:\n- The map shows key wine regions in Italy including Tuscany, Sicily, Piedmont, and others. It is color-coded to indicate elevation, helping to illustrate the diversity of terrain across different wine-producing areas.\n\nThe document appears to be educational, aimed at those interested in understanding more about the variety and classification of Italian wines, and their geographical origins explained on the highlighted map."
