    "source": "vinification_vdn.pdf_page_1",
    "contenu": "The document titled \"Vinification des V.D.N.\" (Technical Sheet No. 19) visually describes the winemaking process for two types of naturally sweet wines: traditional white/rosé wines and traditional red wines, termed here as \"Vins Doux Naturels\" (V.D.N.). The diagrams illustrate the stages of production for each wine type.\n\n### Traditional Winemaking for White/Rosé (Blancs Rosés) wines:\n1. **Mutage Traditionnel**: Grapes undergo traditional mutage, which involves halting fermentation to preserve natural sugars.\n2. **Égrappage**: The grapes are destemmed.\n3. **Foulage**: Crushing of the grapes to release juice.\n4. **Maceration Pelliculaire ou Pressurage Direct**: Skin maceration or direct pressing is done, transitioning into the liquid phase.\n5. **Phase Liquide**: The juice is moved to the liquid phase.\n6. **Débourbage**: Settling or clarification process to remove solids from the juice.\n7. **Fermentation Alcoolique à Température Contrôlée**: Controlled alcoholic fermentation takes place. Optionally, mutage is performed during this liquid phase if desired to make naturally sweet wine.\n\n### Traditional Winemaking for Red (Rouges) wines:\n1. **Mutage Traditionnel**: Similar to the white/rosé process, traditional mutage is applied.\n2. **Égrappage**: Grapes are destemmed.\n3. **Foulage**: Crushing of grapes follows.\n4. **Fermentation Alcoolique à Contrôlée avec Macération**: Controlled alcoholic fermentation with maceration occurs.\n5. **Pressurage**: After fermentation, pressing of the solids is done to extract maximum flavors and colors.\n\nEach diagram is formatted similarly, showcasing the sequence of processes in wine production, with the red wine process including an additional step of pressing after fermentation and controlled maceration. These processes ensure that the naturally sweet wines maintain their sweetness and desired characteristics through careful intervention in their fermentation cycles."
