    "source": "Production_and_Aging_Processes_of__Vins_Doux_Natur",
    "contenu": "The document illustrates two diagrams related to the production and aging processes of \"Vins Doux Naturels\" (naturally sweet wines). Below is a detailed description of the processes depicted in each diagram:\n\n### Upper Diagram: \"Mutage sur Grains\" (Mutage on Skins)\n\n1. **Égrappage** - Removing the stems from the grapes.\n2. **Foulage** - Crushing the grapes to release the juice.\n3. **Fermentation Alcoolique** - The process through which yeast converts the sugars in the grape juice into alcohol. This can either occur in a vat or a barrel.\n4. **Mutage sur Marc** - Addition of alcohol to the grape must to halt fermentation, maintaining a higher level of residual sugar.\n5. **Macération Moyenne de 2 à 4 Semaines** - The skins remain in the must for a maceration period of two to four weeks.\n6. **Pressurage** - Pressing the grape skins to extract juice/must.\n7. **Vin Doux Naturel Fini, Prêt Pour un Éventuel Élevage** - The resulting naturally sweet wine, ready for potential aging processes.\n\n### Lower Diagram: \"Élevage des Vins Doux Naturels\" (Aging of Naturally Sweet Wines)\n\n1. **Élevage** - Wine is aged either in a vat or a barrel, which can be wood (\"Bois\") or stainless steel (\"Inox\"), depending on the desired outcome in terms of wine character and taste.\n2. **Milieu Réducteur** or **Milieu Oxydatif** - Aging in a reductive environment (limiting exposure to oxygen) or oxidative environment (exposing wine to oxygen). This choice affects flavor and texture development.\n3. **Vieillissement** - Further aging possibly in bottles or complemented by additional wooden barrel aging.\n4. **Mise en Bouteilles et Vieillissement Complémentaire** - Final bottling and potential for additional aging to refine the wine further.\n\nThe interactive nature of the diagrams highlights choices during wine production, such as the type of vessel for aging (either reducing or oxidizing environments), demonstrating the craft and detailed decisions behind producing high-quality sweet wines."
