    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_822",
    "contenu": "The given document excerpt discusses two main topics related to proteins, particularly in the context of food molecules:\n\n### 1. PROTEINS IN WATER\n\nProteins in living systems and foods are surrounded by water, which influences their behavior because proteins can hold onto water through hydrogen bonding. The amount of water that proteins can absorb and hold varies depending on the types and amounts of side groups present in the protein. These interactions determine how proteins behave in water, including whether they are soluble or not. Proteins that are insoluble in water tend to have stronger bonds that aren't easily broken by water, leading them to be less soluble. Examples include gluten in flour and muscle fibers in meat, which are held together by iconic and other bonds. In contrast, proteins in milk and eggs are more soluble.\n\n### 2. PROTEIN DENATURATION\n\nThis section details the susceptibility of proteins to denaturation, which involves the unfolding of their original, natural structure due to chemical or physical means. This unfolding leads to the breaking of hydrogen bonds while more extreme conditions are necessary to break the protein's backbone bonds. Denaturation changes a protein's structure but not its composition.\n\nProtein denaturation has various consequences such as coagulation, where denatured proteins bond with each other. This bonding can result in a network that develops into strands, changing the density and texture of the food. Conditions like acidity, heat, or other harsh environments can strengthen these bonds, causing them to shrink and squeeze out water, making the proteins tougher and denser. Various examples of how these processes impact food texture and quality are given, highlighting denaturation and coagulation in practical cooking scenarios.\n\nThese topics elucidate important biochemical processes impacting food's texture, cooking outcomes, and molecular behavior in culinary contexts."
