    "contenu": "# Sesame Seeds\n\n## Introduction\n\n**Sesame Seeds Attributes:**\n- **Aroma Profile:** Woody, herbal, and citrusy aroma.\n- **Usage:** Often toasted or used in baked goods to enhance their flavor, giving nutty, roasted, and caramellike notes.\n\n## Origin and Cultivation\n\n- **Origin:** Native to Africa and widely used in Asia and the Middle East. Sesame plants are the genus *Sesamum*, notably *Sesamum indicum*.\n- **Cultivation:** Grown widely across tropical regions even in areas where other plants are difficult to grow.\n\n## Types and Characteristics\n\n- **Common Varieties:** White sesame (used for oil and organic cultivation) and black sesame (noted for richer, more complex flavor).\n- **Seed Hull:** Majority of seeds are sold already hulled. Unhulled seeds, labeled as 'natural', have a slightly bitter taste.\n\n## Culinary Uses\n\n- **Basic Uses:** Added to breads, crackers, in Japanese, Chinese, and Korean cooking, including both savory dishes and confections.\n- **Middle Eastern Use:** Key ingredient in hummus, baba ghanoush, and halva. Tahini (sesame paste) serves as a dip or sauce.\n- **Japanese Recipes:** Frequently used due to their unique flavor and crunch.\n\n## Special Focus: Sesame Halva\n\n- **Description:** Tahini-based confection from the Eastern Mediterranean and Balkans.\n- **Preparation:** Sugar and honey heated with tahini, blended until smooth, and set in a mold.\n- **Texture and Flavor Additives:** Ingredients like pistachios, cocoa powder, chocolate, vanilla, or orange juice may be included.\n- **Texture:** Can vary from soft and fudgy to gritty and crumbly.\n\n## Related Aroma Profile: Sesame Halva\n\n**Primary Aroma Influences:**\n- Honey provides toast-like, floral, caramellike notes.\n- High concentration of maple and vanilla-scents adds sweetness.\n\n### Sesame Halva Flavor Profile\n\n|                 | Miyabi Melon   | Japanese Muskmelon | Acerola Berry | Camçari | Sencha Tea | Cherry Tomato | Cherry Brandy | Pan-f